<detall><id label=""><![CDATA[106138]]></id><title label="Titol"><![CDATA[A look at the furniture of Palau Güell]]></title><excerpt label="Resum"><![CDATA[<strong>Interior design.</strong> The exhibition is divided into two areas: "The Güell family's decoration” and “The decorators of Catalan Modernisme”.]]></excerpt><content label="Contingut"><![CDATA[<p>The first period covered by the exhibition is when it was owned by Eusebi Güell and his family, and the second, from when it came under the control of Barcelona Provincial Council in 1945 and became a centre showcasing Gaudí and Catalan Modernisme, while compiling furniture from the most important carpenters and decorators of the time.</p>
<p>The Güell i de Sentmenat family has temporarily lent two emblematic pieces, designed by Antoni Gaudí for Palau Güell, for exhibition:  Isabel López&#8217;s chaise longue and one of the original chairs called “of cats and mice”. A modern, terracotta bust, sculpted by M. del Carmen Malet i de Travy as a tribute to the man who would be the family&#8217;s head architect from 1880 to 1918, has also been lent to the exhibition.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
